Microsoft Azure is a comprehensive public cloud computing platform offering over 200 products and services—including AI, analytics, virtual machines, and databases—designed to build, deploy, and manage applications. It enables organizations to rent infrastructure (IaaS), platforms (PaaS), and software (SaaS) on a pay-as-you-go basis via global Microsoft-managed datacenters. 
Key Aspects of Microsoft Azure:
Core Services: Provides essential cloud capabilities such as computing (virtual machines, containers), storage (Blob, File, Disk), and networking.
AI and Analytics: Offers advanced AI tools, machine learning services (Azure AI Studio), and data analytics to drive innovation.
Flexibility and Integration: Supports various programming languages, tools, and frameworks, including third-party software, and integrates with on-premise systems and Active Directory.
Security and Compliance: Features built-in security, including threat intelligence (78 trillion signals daily), with a $20 billion investment in security over five years.
Hybrid and Multi-cloud: Allows businesses to run applications across cloud, on-premises, and edge environments. 
Common Use Cases:
Cloud Migration: Moving existing applications and data to the cloud.
App Development: Building and scaling new applications.
Data Storage and Management: Utilizing managed SQL and NoSQL databases like Cosmos DB.
IoT Solutions: Connecting and managing Internet of Things devices. 